## Simple Definition of the Finnish National Broadway Competition

The Finnish National Broadway Competition (FNB) is an annual musical theater competition held in Finland. It aims to showcase the best Broadway-style musicals produced by Finnish theater groups and encourages creativity, innovation, and collaboration in the musical theater genre.

The competition is open to both professional and amateur theater groups, and it welcomes musicals based on original stories, adapted works, or existing Broadway shows. Each group is allowed to submit one production, with no limitations on the number of cast members or performance length.

Judges evaluate the productions based on various criteria, such as vocals, acting, dance, technical elements, and the overall quality of the production. The winners of the competition are awarded with prize money and the opportunity to perform at the Finnish National Broadway gala event.

The FNB is an excellent opportunity for Finnish theater groups to showcase their talents, network with industry professionals, and gain recognition for their work on a national stage.
